1
00:03:15,280 --> 00:03:17,440
You know,
I just had a thought.

2
00:03:18,720 --> 00:03:21,040
Why don't I check in a hotel
and rest.

3
00:03:21,080 --> 00:03:24,120
- You go find your folks.
- Oh, John.

4
00:03:24,200 --> 00:03:26,160
You wanted to meet them.
Let's go meet them.

5
00:03:26,240 --> 00:03:28,080
The sooner we get it over with,
the better.

6
00:03:28,160 --> 00:03:30,560
Mom may not even be at the gallery.
She'll probably be out to lunch.

7
00:03:30,640 --> 00:03:32,920
Dad's at his office. You may not
meet them till dinner anyway.

8
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:35,000
You may be wrong about them.

9
00:03:35,080 --> 00:03:37,560
You should have called
and told them we were coming.

10
00:03:37,600 --> 00:03:40,760
You may be in for the biggest shock
of your young life.

11
00:03:40,800 --> 00:03:43,280
After 23 years living
in the same house with them...

12
00:03:43,360 --> 00:03:45,680
don't you think I know
my own mother and father?

13
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:47,680
I hope so.

14
00:03:47,760 --> 00:03:49,840
There's no problem.

15
00:04:01,800 --> 00:04:05,160
We'll only be a minute, and then
we'd like to go out to Claremont Drive.

16
00:04:05,240 --> 00:04:06,760
Right.

17
00:04:12,640 --> 00:04:15,000
I'll see if Mom's
in the office.

18
00:04:22,080 --> 00:04:24,960
- Joey!
- Hilary, hi! How are you?

19
00:04:25,040 --> 00:04:27,600
What a surprise.

20
00:04:27,680 --> 00:04:30,000
- I'll be with you in just a moment.
- Okay.

21
00:04:37,560 --> 00:04:40,560
- Strange.
- One of Hilary's favorites.

22
00:04:40,600 --> 00:04:43,200
It's called a kinetic sculpture.

23
00:04:43,280 --> 00:04:45,120
- A what?
- Look.

24
00:04:47,960 --> 00:04:49,840
Why, isn't that something?

25
00:04:53,320 --> 00:04:56,600
- Darling, what are you doing here?
- I thought Mother might be here.

26
00:04:56,640 --> 00:04:59,680
Mrs. St. George, I'd like you
to meet Dr. Prentice.

27
00:04:59,720 --> 00:05:01,920
Dr. Prentice,
I'm so pleased to meet you.

28
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,280
Mrs. St. George.
Pleasure to see you.

29
00:05:05,760 --> 00:05:07,800
Christina's lunching
with Mr. Cazalet.

30
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:09,280
I can ring up.

31
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:11,440
No. Just tell her I'm back
and that I'll be home.

32
00:05:11,520 --> 00:05:15,520
Has something happened?
I mean, is anything wrong?

33
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:18,080
Something's happened,
but everything's right. Thanks.

34
00:05:18,160 --> 00:05:21,960
How was Hawaii?
Was it fun?

35
00:05:22,040 --> 00:05:24,200
Hawaii was simply unbelievable.

36
00:05:25,960 --> 00:05:29,320
Do you live in San Francisco, Doctor,
or are you just visiting?

37
00:05:29,400 --> 00:05:31,280
- I'm just passing through.
- I see.

38
00:05:31,360 --> 00:05:33,720
- It was a pleasure to have met you.
- Thank you.

39
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:34,840
Bye-bye.

40
00:05:57,360 --> 00:06:01,360
No, Hilary runs the gallery now,
but it's Mom who has all the ideas.

41
00:06:01,440 --> 00:06:04,480
Her idea for filling hotel rooms
with originals is brilliant.

42
00:06:04,560 --> 00:06:07,840
It gives people who stay there
time to decide if they want them.

43
00:06:07,920 --> 00:06:09,760
The hotel gets supplied
with free decor.

44
00:06:09,840 --> 00:06:12,800
The guests get to look at good paintings
instead of bad reproductions.

45
00:06:12,840 --> 00:06:16,120
The painter gets a chance to make a sale
and Mom gets her commission.

46
00:06:16,200 --> 00:06:17,240
Next right.

47
00:06:18,400 --> 00:06:21,080
- Isn't that clever?
- Oh, that is clever.

48
00:07:02,960 --> 00:07:05,320
- What do I owe you?
- 10.50, mac.

49
00:07:06,600 --> 00:07:08,440
Twelve bucks, right?

50
00:07:10,440 --> 00:07:12,280
Right.

51
00:07:13,320 --> 00:07:14,840
Right.

52
00:07:15,760 --> 00:07:17,640
Oh, John.
Come meet Tillie.

53
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:25,120
Tillie, this is Dr. Prentice.
John, Miss Matilda Binks.

54
00:07:25,160 --> 00:07:27,120
Pleased to meet you, Miss Binks.

55
00:07:27,200 --> 00:07:30,600
I've certainly heard
a great deal about you.

56
00:07:30,680 --> 00:07:32,560
What are you
doing home unexpected?

57
00:07:32,600 --> 00:07:35,440
Your folks didn't know you was coming.
You told them you're back already?

58
00:07:35,440 --> 00:07:37,560
I left a message for Mom
at the gallery.

59
00:07:37,640 --> 00:07:39,600
It's lovely to see you.
I missed you.

60
00:07:39,680 --> 00:07:41,720
You still ain't told me
why you're home early.

61
00:07:41,800 --> 00:07:44,640
- You want those bags to go upstairs?
- Not my two. I'm not staying.

62
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:47,600
It's personal reasons.
I'll tell you all about it.

63
00:07:47,640 --> 00:07:50,520
You eat any lunch yet,
or you expecting it now?

64
00:07:50,600 --> 00:07:54,640
Could you make us sandwiches and coffee?
We'll have it on the terrace.

65
00:08:17,520 --> 00:08:19,360
Do you like it?

66
00:08:20,640 --> 00:08:22,520
It's beautiful.

67
00:08:22,600 --> 00:08:24,600
Come out
and look from the terrace.

68
00:08:29,840 --> 00:08:33,120
- What?
- Hey, who's that?

69
00:08:36,640 --> 00:08:40,720
That's Dorothy. Isn't she a knockout?
She helps Tillie during the week.

70
00:08:40,800 --> 00:08:43,120
- Which days?
- Never mind.

71
00:08:47,760 --> 00:08:50,880
You know, I ought to call my folks
and get that out of the way.

72
00:08:50,960 --> 00:08:52,800
Okay. Use the phone in the study.

73
00:08:52,880 --> 00:08:55,800
- Are you gonna introduce me?
- Not on the phone.

74
00:08:55,880 --> 00:08:58,120
- Aren't you gonna tell them about me?
- I'd rather write to them.

75
00:08:58,200 --> 00:09:01,640
I have to meet them, don't I?
Before I come to Geneva?

76
00:09:01,720 --> 00:09:05,480
Or are we going to keep our marriage
a secret from them?

77
00:09:05,520 --> 00:09:07,840
Why didn't I think of that?
See, that's a thought.

78
00:09:08,920 --> 00:09:11,720
I'll shut this
in case Dorothy goes by.

79
00:09:47,680 --> 00:09:50,080
Los Angeles, please.
Area code 213.

80
00:09:50,160 --> 00:09:53,320
Axminster, two, four, six, nine, nine.
Time and charges.

81
00:09:53,400 --> 00:09:56,000
Well, I got a right
to my own opinions.

82
00:09:56,080 --> 00:09:57,800
And you want my opinion?

83
00:09:57,800 --> 00:10:01,120
I don't care to see a member
of my own race getting above hisself.

84
00:10:01,160 --> 00:10:04,640
Then I don't want your opinion,
and if I ever do, I'll ask for it.

85
00:10:04,720 --> 00:10:07,360
Oh, Tillie, I'm sorry.

86
00:10:07,440 --> 00:10:11,000
I didn't mean that, but you can't mean
what you're saying either.

87
00:10:11,080 --> 00:10:13,280
And you're so wrong.
Look.

88
00:10:13,360 --> 00:10:18,280
You're the last person I'd have expected
to take such a silly attitude.

89
00:10:18,320 --> 00:10:22,280
You know I've always loved you,
and you're just as black as he is.

90
00:10:22,360 --> 00:10:26,080
How could it be all right for me to
love you and wrong for me to love him?

91
00:10:26,160 --> 00:10:29,360
Will you just stop
and think about that?

92
00:10:29,440 --> 00:10:31,680
Listen. What are we having
for dinner tonight?

93
00:10:31,760 --> 00:10:34,120
- Gotta make it something special.
- Celery soup and rump steak.

94
00:10:34,200 --> 00:10:37,360
Oh, now, come on.
Turtle soup and tournedos...

95
00:10:37,400 --> 00:10:40,160
and one of your best pies.

96
00:10:40,240 --> 00:10:42,120
It's Mom!

97
00:10:43,160 --> 00:10:47,440
Joey, darling.
What the hell? Joey!

98
00:10:47,440 --> 00:10:49,880
- Mom, I'm here!
- Hello, darling. Are you all right?

99
00:10:49,960 --> 00:10:52,960
- There's nothing wrong, is there?
- Nothing's wrong. Everything's fine.

100
00:10:53,040 --> 00:10:56,480
I rang the gallery to tell Hilary
that Cazalet agreed to our scheme.

101
00:10:56,560 --> 00:10:59,560
He has? That's marvelous.
I knew he would.

102
00:10:59,600 --> 00:11:02,720
She said you were back. She thought
you might have a surprise for me.

103
00:11:02,800 --> 00:11:05,440
What did she mean?
Do I hear someone?

104
00:11:05,520 --> 00:11:08,440
- Is there someone here?
- Oh, Mom, I'm so happy.

105
00:11:08,520 --> 00:11:11,400
I've never been so happy in all my life.
I'm just...

106
00:11:11,480 --> 00:11:14,080
Bursting. Yeah, I can see that.

107
00:11:14,160 --> 00:11:16,920
And I'm already feeling happy for you.
Do I know him?

108
00:11:16,960 --> 00:11:20,040
No. That's just it.
I only met him myself ten days ago.

109
00:11:20,120 --> 00:11:22,960
You wouldn't believe what's happened
in just ten days.

110
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:27,600
I think I might if you'd pipe down
long enough to tell me.

111
00:11:27,680 --> 00:11:29,520
- Mom...
- Lots of wonderful things happen...

112
00:11:29,600 --> 00:11:32,160
He's so wonderful!

113
00:11:32,200 --> 00:11:35,640
I've never known anyone like him.
Never known anything like this.

114
00:11:35,720 --> 00:11:39,440
I fell in love with him
in 20 minutes.

115
00:11:39,520 --> 00:11:42,160
Well, that was quick.

116
00:11:43,440 --> 00:11:46,080
Well, Dad, I wanted to stop
on the way back...

117
00:11:46,160 --> 00:11:49,840
but time got so short
and I've got to get to work.

118
00:11:49,920 --> 00:11:55,080
Yeah, but I still don't understand
why you couldn't spend one day with us.

119
00:11:55,160 --> 00:11:59,760
Well, the fact is, Dad,
I met this girl.

120
00:11:59,800 --> 00:12:02,440
You what? You met a girl?
Why didn't you say so?

121
00:12:02,520 --> 00:12:05,880
Mary, he says he met a girl.
Why, that's good news.

122
00:12:05,960 --> 00:12:09,280
- She live up there in San Francisco?
- She lives up here. I'm at her house.

123
00:12:09,360 --> 00:12:11,600
He says he's at her house now,
the girl's house.

124
00:12:11,680 --> 00:12:14,280
Well, that's different, son.
Where'd you meet her? Hawaii?

125
00:12:14,360 --> 00:12:17,720
Yes, in Hawaii,
and I wanted to meet her folks, see?

126
00:12:17,800 --> 00:12:19,840
That sounds good, son.
I mean, serious.

127
00:12:19,920 --> 00:12:22,640
Yes, it's serious.

128
00:12:22,720 --> 00:12:24,560
Well, this is quite a surprise.

129
00:12:24,640 --> 00:12:27,280
Yeah, she's surprising
in a lot of ways, Dad.

130
00:12:27,360 --> 00:12:29,280
Your mother says,
"Is she pretty? '

131
00:12:29,360 --> 00:12:32,160
- Yes, she's very pretty.
- She's pretty. What?

132
00:12:32,240 --> 00:12:34,160
Your mother says,
"How old is she, son?"

133
00:12:34,200 --> 00:12:36,200
Mary, what the hell difference
does that make?

134
00:12:36,280 --> 00:12:38,720
Well, she's only 23, Dad.

135
00:12:38,800 --> 00:12:40,760
Twenty-three. Well, that's good.
You want my opinion?

136
00:12:40,840 --> 00:12:43,000
You're 37.
That's just the right difference.

137
00:12:43,040 --> 00:12:45,440
Women age faster than men,
you know what I mean?

138
00:12:45,520 --> 00:12:49,200
- You reckon to marry the girl, son?
- Well, we've been talking about it.

139
00:12:49,240 --> 00:12:51,360
But...

140
00:12:51,440 --> 00:12:55,720
Dad, there's one or two problems,
you see?

141
00:12:57,120 --> 00:12:59,200
That I'll write to you about...

142
00:12:59,280 --> 00:13:03,040
on the plane to New York tonight,
all right?

143
00:13:04,200 --> 00:13:06,160
He's so calm...

144
00:13:06,240 --> 00:13:09,200
and sure of everything.

145
00:13:09,240 --> 00:13:12,040
He doesn't have
any tensions in him.

146
00:13:12,120 --> 00:13:13,960
He knows what he believes...

147
00:13:14,040 --> 00:13:18,520
and what he thinks is right
and why and where he's going.

148
00:13:19,680 --> 00:13:22,520
Oh, Mom, there's one thing
I must tell you.

149
00:13:22,600 --> 00:13:26,360
He was married before,
and he had a son.

150
00:13:26,440 --> 00:13:28,040
It was so tragic.

151
00:13:29,640 --> 00:13:32,440
Both his wife and his son were killed
in a train accident...

152
00:13:32,520 --> 00:13:34,400
in Belgium eight years ago.

153
00:13:35,440 --> 00:13:37,800
And John...

154
00:13:37,840 --> 00:13:40,280
I haven't even told you
his name.

155
00:13:42,200 --> 00:13:45,680
Mom, it's John Wade Prentice.

156
00:13:45,720 --> 00:13:47,600
Isn't that a lovely name?

157
00:13:47,680 --> 00:13:49,400
John Wade...

158
00:13:50,720 --> 00:13:52,080
Joanna Prentice...

159
00:13:52,160 --> 00:13:53,560
I'll be.

160
00:13:54,960 --> 00:13:57,720
But Mom...

161
00:13:57,800 --> 00:14:00,000
there's something else
that I must tell you...

162
00:14:00,080 --> 00:14:03,760
that John's been concerned about,
very deeply concerned.

163
00:14:03,840 --> 00:14:08,240
He's been worrying for the past week
whether you and Dad would be upset if...

164
00:14:08,320 --> 00:14:10,720
Well, it's about time.

165
00:14:10,800 --> 00:14:13,000
I was wondering where you'd been.

166
00:14:13,080 --> 00:14:14,600
Mom...

167
00:14:15,720 --> 00:14:17,560
this is John.

168
00:14:19,280 --> 00:14:22,600
Doctor Prentice...

169
00:14:22,640 --> 00:14:26,200
I'm so pleased to meet you.

170
00:14:26,280 --> 00:14:29,440
I'm pleased to meet you,
Mrs. Drayton.

171
00:14:29,520 --> 00:14:32,600
I take it Joanna's already busted out
with the big news.

172
00:14:32,680 --> 00:14:37,400
Well, she has told me a good deal
and all very quickly too.

173
00:14:37,440 --> 00:14:41,120
Well, she's only known me
for ten days...

174
00:14:41,200 --> 00:14:43,440
so she can't tell you
when I'm blushing.

175
00:14:43,480 --> 00:14:46,080
That could be another problem
for us.

176
00:14:50,160 --> 00:14:52,440
Mrs. Drayton,
I'm medically qualified...

177
00:14:52,520 --> 00:14:54,920
so I hope you wouldn't
think it presumptuous if I say...

178
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:57,120
you ought to sit down
before you fall down.

179
00:14:57,200 --> 00:14:59,320
He thinks you're gonna faint
because he's a Negro.

180
00:15:00,960 --> 00:15:02,200
Well...

181
00:15:02,240 --> 00:15:04,640
I don't think
I'm going to faint.

182
00:15:06,640 --> 00:15:08,680
But I'll sit down anyway.

183
00:15:15,440 --> 00:15:17,920
Can't we all sit down?

184
00:15:31,320 --> 00:15:32,600
Well...

185
00:15:34,120 --> 00:15:39,400
I suppose it would be all right
if I said, "My goodness," wouldn't it?

186
00:15:40,720 --> 00:15:42,080
Well, my goodness.

187
00:15:42,880 --> 00:15:46,200
- Do we mind her saying, "My goodness"?
- I don't mind.

188
00:15:46,280 --> 00:15:48,200
What did they say?
Did you tell them about me?

189
00:15:48,280 --> 00:15:49,360
- Yes.
- What'd they say?

190
00:15:49,440 --> 00:15:52,800
They said I sounded serious
and asked if you were pretty.

191
00:15:52,880 --> 00:15:54,240
I said you were.

192
00:15:54,320 --> 00:15:56,840
They said this was a big surprise.

193
00:15:56,920 --> 00:15:58,640
I said it was.

194
00:15:58,680 --> 00:16:01,320
Well, what did they say when you
told them I wasn't a colored girl?

195
00:16:01,400 --> 00:16:04,000
I didn't. It felt like
too big a shock for the telephone.

196
00:16:04,040 --> 00:16:07,120
After all, a lot of people will think
that we're a very shocking pair.

197
00:16:07,200 --> 00:16:08,440
Isn't that right?

198
00:16:08,520 --> 00:16:11,160
I know what you mean.

199
00:16:13,560 --> 00:16:15,160
Tillie's made us some sandwiches.

200
00:16:15,240 --> 00:16:17,120
- Let's go outside.
- Yes, let's.

201
00:16:17,200 --> 00:16:21,040
- Come on, Dr. Prentice.
- I can explain it all in two minutes.

202
00:16:21,120 --> 00:16:24,320
You see, John was invited to lecture
at Hawaii University...

203
00:16:24,400 --> 00:16:26,280
and we met at this big party
at the dean's.

204
00:16:26,320 --> 00:16:28,640
After the party,
we went for a long drive.

205
00:16:28,720 --> 00:16:31,640
- Thank you.
- And since then, we've been together.

206
00:16:31,680 --> 00:16:34,120
We've been swimming every day.

207
00:16:34,200 --> 00:16:37,920
Then John was supposed to fly back to
Los Angeles Saturday to see his parents.

208
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:39,520
That's where they live.

209
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:42,720
Thank you, Tillie.

210
00:16:46,200 --> 00:16:49,320
Try one of these.
They're great.

211
00:16:49,400 --> 00:16:51,520
- Do you want some coffee?
- No, thanks. No coffee.

212
00:16:51,600 --> 00:16:53,520
Does your father know
that you're back?

213
00:16:53,600 --> 00:16:56,000
No, I was going to phone him.
Do you think he'd come back early if...

214
00:16:56,080 --> 00:16:59,400
He's coming back early, all right.
He's playing golf with Monsignor Ryan.

215
00:16:59,440 --> 00:17:00,800
That's marvelous.

216
00:17:00,880 --> 00:17:03,760
Then he can meet John
and we can all talk over dinner...

217
00:17:03,840 --> 00:17:06,560
because John has to fly
to New York tonight to see a friend...

218
00:17:06,600 --> 00:17:08,080
at Columbia University.

219
00:17:08,160 --> 00:17:10,080
Then tomorrow night,
he's flying to Geneva...

220
00:17:10,120 --> 00:17:12,560
to do three month's work
for the World Health Organization.

221
00:17:12,640 --> 00:17:16,760
And I intend to fly to Geneva next week
so that we can be married.

222
00:17:16,840 --> 00:17:18,680
And that's the whole situation.

223
00:17:18,760 --> 00:17:20,800
In a nutshell.

224
00:17:20,840 --> 00:17:22,360
Except that he thinks...

225
00:17:22,440 --> 00:17:24,960
that the fact he's a Negro and I'm not
creates a serious problem.

226
00:17:25,960 --> 00:17:27,000
Does he?

227
00:17:27,080 --> 00:17:29,280
I've told him 97 times...

228
00:17:29,360 --> 00:17:31,680
that it wouldn't make the slightest
difference to you or Dad.

229
00:17:31,760 --> 00:17:34,880
But he just wouldn't believe me.
So that's why we're here.

230
00:17:35,720 --> 00:17:37,840
And that's why he's watching you
so closely right now...

231
00:17:37,880 --> 00:17:40,240
while he's pretending
not to watch you at all.

232
00:17:43,120 --> 00:17:45,680
She's absolutely right, Mrs. Drayton.
I'm sorry.

233
00:17:45,760 --> 00:17:47,640
I told her not to spring all this
on you so suddenly.

234
00:17:47,720 --> 00:17:50,080
But... Look,
if your father's coming home...

235
00:17:50,160 --> 00:17:52,480
you could at least say
that I'm somebody you met in Hawaii.

236
00:17:52,560 --> 00:17:55,080
- Now, really?
- Give him a half hour to get adjusted.

237
00:17:55,160 --> 00:17:58,360
But what for?
He still has to be told, doesn't he?

238
00:18:00,080 --> 00:18:03,840
Well, you should make up your minds
because I think I just heard his car.

239
00:18:08,640 --> 00:18:10,040
Mr. Matt.

240
00:18:10,080 --> 00:18:12,480
- Hi. How are you?
- All hell's done broke loose.

241
00:18:12,560 --> 00:18:14,720
- That waste disposal out again?
- It ain't that.

242
00:18:14,800 --> 00:18:16,440
Just remember,
all hell's done broke loose.

243
00:18:16,480 --> 00:18:19,800
- What's happened? Where's Christina?
- She's on the terrace with little Joey.

244
00:18:19,880 --> 00:18:23,040
- With Joey?
- And somebody called Dr. Prentice.

245
00:18:23,120 --> 00:18:25,240
Doctor? There's a doc...

246
00:18:25,320 --> 00:18:27,360
Well, what's wrong?
What's happened? Joey!

247
00:18:30,040 --> 00:18:31,400
Here he comes.

248
00:18:31,480 --> 00:18:35,000
- Daddy! How are you?
- What's happened? What are you doing?

249
00:18:35,080 --> 00:18:38,240
- Tillie said there was a doctor here.
- There is! Dr. John Wade Prentice.

250
00:18:38,280 --> 00:18:39,880
- This is my dad.
- Pleased to meet you.

251
00:18:39,960 --> 00:18:41,760
How are you? Nice to know you.
But what is it?

252
00:18:41,840 --> 00:18:43,880
- Is something wrong?
- There's nothing wrong.

253
00:18:43,960 --> 00:18:45,320
I decided to come home early.

254
00:18:45,400 --> 00:18:48,200
Oh, Dr. Prentice and I
met in Hawaii...

255
00:18:48,280 --> 00:18:49,920
and we flew back in the same plane
this morning.

256
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:53,320
Oh, well, sit down.

257
00:18:53,360 --> 00:18:55,000
I thought something was really wrong.
Tillie said...

258
00:18:55,040 --> 00:18:57,720
Tillie's behaving very strangely today.
Would you like coffee?

259
00:18:57,800 --> 00:19:01,960
No, thanks. I have a date to play golf
with Monsignor Ryan.

260
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:04,680
How are you? What's the matter,
you having a chill?

261
00:19:04,720 --> 00:19:06,640
No, darling, I'm fine.

262
00:19:06,680 --> 00:19:08,520
I...

263
00:19:08,560 --> 00:19:11,960
Doctor, where are you practicing?
In San Francisco?

264
00:19:12,040 --> 00:19:14,120
- Sit down.
- No, sir.

265
00:19:14,120 --> 00:19:16,680
I'm just here for one day.

266
00:19:16,760 --> 00:19:19,560
Oh, where is your practice?
Hawaii?

267
00:19:19,640 --> 00:19:24,400
Well, no, not...
I'm not established in any one place.

268
00:19:24,440 --> 00:19:26,760
I'm in tropical medicines, mostly,
in Africa...

269
00:19:26,840 --> 00:19:28,040
these past few years.

270
00:19:28,120 --> 00:19:30,240
Well, that sounds interesting.

271
00:19:30,320 --> 00:19:32,480
Everything about Dr. Prentice
is interesting.

272
00:19:32,520 --> 00:19:34,320
I'm sure it is.

273
00:19:34,400 --> 00:19:36,400
I wish I had more time,
but if you'll excuse me.

274
00:19:36,480 --> 00:19:38,560
Couldn't you be a half hour late
and stay and talk with us?

275
00:19:38,640 --> 00:19:41,000
I'd love to, but I mustn't keep
the Monsignor waiting.

276
00:19:41,080 --> 00:19:43,360
No, I'm gonna be late as it is.
Will I be seeing you later, Doctor?

277
00:19:43,440 --> 00:19:45,560
You certainly will.

278
00:19:45,600 --> 00:19:47,040
Good.
Well, that's good.

279
00:19:47,120 --> 00:19:49,360
Dr. Prentice will be here
for dinner, Matt.

280
00:19:49,440 --> 00:19:51,760
Oh, fine. Then you can tell me
all about the African...

281
00:19:51,800 --> 00:19:53,880
There's a great deal to tell too.
Isn't there, Mom?

282
00:19:57,400 --> 00:19:59,640
Well, fine.
See you all later.

283
00:20:25,680 --> 00:20:27,520
What the hell
is going on here?

284
00:20:29,040 --> 00:20:31,600
- This doesn't make sense either.
- Well, I told you, didn't I?

285
00:20:31,680 --> 00:20:33,560
What'd you tell him?
Look, Chris...

286
00:20:33,640 --> 00:20:35,600
if you don't explain to me
in the next few minutes...

287
00:20:35,680 --> 00:20:37,920
I can explain it, Mr. Drayton.

288
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:39,880
You can?
Well, let's have it

289
00:20:39,960 --> 00:20:41,800
Well, it's my fault.

290
00:20:43,120 --> 00:20:45,600
You see,
we have sort of a situation here.

291
00:20:46,760 --> 00:20:48,840
Joanna and I didn't just meet
in Hawaii.

292
00:20:48,920 --> 00:20:50,760
We spend a good deal of time
together.

293
00:20:51,880 --> 00:20:55,160
I mean, all the time
after we met.

294
00:20:55,240 --> 00:20:58,560
And, well, we have this problem:

295
00:20:59,600 --> 00:21:01,720
I fell in love with your daughter.

296
00:21:04,560 --> 00:21:07,560
And, as incredible
as it may seem...

297
00:21:07,600 --> 00:21:10,600
she fell in love with me.

298
00:21:11,280 --> 00:21:13,920
And we flew back
to San Francisco...

299
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:17,760
to see if you or Mrs. Drayton would have
any objections if we got married.

300
00:21:23,040 --> 00:21:25,400
Joanna told her mother
as soon as she walked in...

301
00:21:25,480 --> 00:21:28,240
and I had the stupid idea,
that maybe...

302
00:21:28,280 --> 00:21:31,160
there was some way to...

303
00:21:31,200 --> 00:21:34,360
break this gently.

304
00:21:51,120 --> 00:21:53,120
Daddy, you're making
John and me nervous.

305
00:21:53,200 --> 00:21:56,400
Am I?
Well, I wouldn't want to do that.

306
00:21:56,440 --> 00:21:59,720
I wouldn't want to make anybody nervous.
How about you? Are you nervous?

307
00:21:59,760 --> 00:22:02,600
Sit down, Doctor,
before you make me nervous.

308
00:22:05,680 --> 00:22:08,480
Would anybody like
a cup of coffee?

309
00:22:08,560 --> 00:22:13,200
What did she say
when Joanna told her?

310
00:22:13,240 --> 00:22:17,160
- Did she raise any objections?
- None, so far. There hasn't been time.

311
00:22:17,240 --> 00:22:19,160
What objections?

312
00:22:19,240 --> 00:22:23,240
Dad, I know this is sort of a shock
because it's sudden and unexpected...

313
00:22:23,280 --> 00:22:26,120
and it never occurred to me
that I might fall in love with a Negro.

314
00:22:26,160 --> 00:22:29,840
But I did, and nothing in the world
is gonna change that.

315
00:22:29,880 --> 00:22:33,440
Even if you had any objections,
I wouldn't let him go now if...

316
00:22:33,520 --> 00:22:36,360
you were the governor of Alabama...
I mean, if Mom were.

317
00:22:37,840 --> 00:22:39,240
Tell him, will you?

318
00:22:39,280 --> 00:22:42,520
Tell John if you have any objections
and then you could go play golf.

319
00:22:42,600 --> 00:22:46,320
Well, what is it
you expect me to say?

320
00:22:46,400 --> 00:22:49,280
If you want me to think about this,
you'll have to give me time to think.

321
00:22:49,360 --> 00:22:52,080
The doctor says you have a problem.
You certainly have.

322
00:22:52,160 --> 00:22:55,840
If you're expecting a sensible
statement, you'll have to give me time.

323
00:22:55,880 --> 00:22:57,760
Does that sound reasonable?

324
00:22:57,800 --> 00:23:01,160
It's reasonable, Mr. Drayton,
but not quite practical.

325
00:23:02,200 --> 00:23:04,200
You see, Matt...

326
00:23:04,280 --> 00:23:07,080
there's sort of
a special problem.

327
00:23:07,120 --> 00:23:09,720
See, I've got to fly
to New York tonight...

328
00:23:09,800 --> 00:23:11,680
and on to Switzerland
tomorrow night.

329
00:23:11,720 --> 00:23:14,880
Yes, and what Joey wants...
what she proposes...

330
00:23:14,960 --> 00:23:17,880
is to go to Geneva herself
so they can be married...

331
00:23:17,960 --> 00:23:19,840
within the next couple of weeks.

332
00:23:19,920 --> 00:23:21,880
What the hell is all the rush?

333
00:23:21,960 --> 00:23:23,840
We know that we want
to get married.

334
00:23:23,880 --> 00:23:27,400
And unless somebody does have any
objections, why should we waste time?

335
00:23:27,480 --> 00:23:29,320
John and I aren't gonna
change our minds.

336
00:23:30,440 --> 00:23:32,840
Are you saying...
Are you telling me...

337
00:23:32,920 --> 00:23:35,600
that you want an answer today...

338
00:23:35,680 --> 00:23:37,520
about how your mother and I feel?

339
00:23:37,600 --> 00:23:41,760
Of course. We want you and Mom
to state absolutely clearly...

340
00:23:41,800 --> 00:23:43,400
that you have
no objections whatever...

341
00:23:43,480 --> 00:23:46,840
and that when we do get married,
we'll have your blessing.

342
00:23:55,760 --> 00:23:58,520
Now, are you gonna play golf
or not?

343
00:23:58,600 --> 00:24:00,080
No.

344
00:24:00,160 --> 00:24:02,520
I'll just call it off.
Excuse me, Doctor.

345
00:24:08,280 --> 00:24:11,600
And that's my dad.
Do you like him?

346
00:24:11,680 --> 00:24:14,760
- I don't know. Does he like me?
- I don't know either.

347
00:24:14,840 --> 00:24:16,720
When he puts on
his American eagle face...

348
00:24:16,760 --> 00:24:18,960
nobody can tell what he's thinking,
except Mom.

349
00:24:19,040 --> 00:24:22,360
I don't think he liked any of us
after the silly way we began.

350
00:24:22,440 --> 00:24:25,040
Excuse me, will you?
Give John some more coffee.

351
00:24:25,080 --> 00:24:27,320
She's beautiful, Joanna.

352
00:24:27,360 --> 00:24:29,640
She's even better looking than you.
You know that?

353
00:24:29,720 --> 00:24:32,040
Hello, Edie?

354
00:24:32,120 --> 00:24:34,600
Two things, Edie.
Both of them urgent.

355
00:24:34,680 --> 00:24:38,480
Call up Monsignor Ryan and tell him
I can't play this afternoon.

356
00:24:38,520 --> 00:24:42,560
Tell him something's come up,
something personal at home.

357
00:24:42,600 --> 00:24:43,960
Then call the library...

358
00:24:44,040 --> 00:24:47,280
and see if they've got any dope
on a John Wade Prentice.

359
00:24:47,360 --> 00:24:52,000
Prentice. He's a doctor of medicine.
Fellow about 35, 36...

360
00:24:52,040 --> 00:24:54,600
- Oh, Matt.
- He's a colored fellow.

361
00:24:54,680 --> 00:24:57,440
Yeah.
If they haven't got anything...

362
00:24:57,520 --> 00:25:00,000
call up the medical association
and see what they've got.

363
00:25:00,080 --> 00:25:03,680
Get anything you can, will you, Edie?
All right. Hurry and call me back.

364
00:25:03,760 --> 00:25:06,160
Surely there can't be
any necessity for that.

365
00:25:06,240 --> 00:25:10,880
- It can't do any harm, either.
- But Joey said he was lecturing...

366
00:25:10,960 --> 00:25:12,440
at the university in Hawaii.

367
00:25:12,520 --> 00:25:15,320
Tell me something. This ever occur
to you that this might happen?

368
00:25:18,120 --> 00:25:21,280
Never occurred to me either.
Not once.

369
00:25:23,320 --> 00:25:24,760
Can you tell me your reaction?

370
00:25:24,840 --> 00:25:28,000
- How do you feel about it?
- Oh, I don't know.

371
00:25:28,080 --> 00:25:30,240
I was shaken at first.
I still am, I suppose.

372
00:25:30,320 --> 00:25:32,760
But, Matt, they're serious.
They mean what they're saying.

373
00:25:32,840 --> 00:25:34,680
Both of them.
They know what they're doing.

374
00:25:34,760 --> 00:25:37,360
No, they may mean what they're saying,
I accept that.

375
00:25:37,440 --> 00:25:40,080
But they don't know what they're doing.
I won't accept that.

376
00:25:42,920 --> 00:25:44,480
If I'm not intruding...

377
00:25:45,280 --> 00:25:47,680
Of course not.
Please, come in.

378
00:25:47,760 --> 00:25:50,840
I'd like to have a couple of minutes
with the two of you, if I may?

379
00:25:50,880 --> 00:25:52,760
Sure, Doctor.
Come on in.

380
00:25:55,440 --> 00:26:00,040
There's something you both
ought to know. I made a decision.

381
00:26:00,960 --> 00:26:03,720
Joanna doesn't know about it,
and I don't see why she should.

382
00:26:04,400 --> 00:26:06,040
What is it, Doctor?

383
00:26:06,120 --> 00:26:08,160
Joanna thinks she's committed...

384
00:26:08,240 --> 00:26:10,440
and that our whole future
is settled...

385
00:26:10,520 --> 00:26:12,680
but there is no real commitment.

386
00:26:12,760 --> 00:26:15,320
And up to now,
nothing is settled at all.

387
00:26:16,360 --> 00:26:17,760
I don't understand.

388
00:26:17,840 --> 00:26:20,720
Joanna said you're going to be married
no matter what we think about it.

389
00:26:21,440 --> 00:26:23,560
Well, that's not the case.

390
00:26:23,640 --> 00:26:26,520
Unless you two approve...
and without any reservations at all...

391
00:26:26,600 --> 00:26:27,920
there won't be any marriage.

392
00:26:29,680 --> 00:26:31,960
Well, why, John?

393
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:33,880
Why have you decided that?

394
00:26:35,160 --> 00:26:36,360
Well, Mrs. Drayton...

395
00:26:36,440 --> 00:26:38,640
this thing has happened so quickly...

396
00:26:38,720 --> 00:26:41,440
I'm just as startled
as you must be.

397
00:26:41,520 --> 00:26:44,280
Two weeks ago, I would have said
such a thing was inconceivable.

398
00:26:45,440 --> 00:26:47,360
But two weeks ago...

399
00:26:47,400 --> 00:26:49,280
I had not met Joanna.

400
00:26:50,520 --> 00:26:54,920
She's not at all
like anyone I've ever known.

401
00:26:55,720 --> 00:26:58,920
It's not just that our color difference
doesn't matter to her.

402
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:01,800
It's that she doesn't seem to think
there is any difference.

403
00:27:05,760 --> 00:27:07,600
The trouble is,
this thing has come up...

404
00:27:07,680 --> 00:27:11,120
at a time when I already have
all the problems I need.

405
00:27:11,160 --> 00:27:13,200
And I feel that I couldn't afford
to get married...

406
00:27:13,280 --> 00:27:16,240
if it meant that I would have to take
on any special problems...

407
00:27:16,320 --> 00:27:19,080
in addition to those
we're obviously going to have.

408
00:27:20,640 --> 00:27:23,960
When you say "special problems,"
Doctor, what do you mean?

409
00:27:25,120 --> 00:27:26,680
Well...

410
00:27:30,720 --> 00:27:33,080
Your attitude, Mr. Drayton...

411
00:27:34,160 --> 00:27:36,040
and yours, Mrs. Drayton.

412
00:27:37,440 --> 00:27:40,160
Joanna is very close
to both of you.

413
00:27:41,280 --> 00:27:44,960
If, by marrying me, she damaged
her relationship with either of you...

414
00:27:45,040 --> 00:27:47,640
the pain of it
would be too much for her.

415
00:27:48,760 --> 00:27:51,480
I wouldn't know how to deal
with that kind of situation.

416
00:27:51,560 --> 00:27:53,920
In any case,
I wouldn't even want to try.

417
00:27:57,520 --> 00:27:59,520
Well, I'm glad you told us,
Doctor.

418
00:28:02,160 --> 00:28:05,520
Don't misunderstand me.
I love your daughter.

419
00:28:05,600 --> 00:28:09,640
There is nothing I wouldn't do to keep
her as happy as she was the day we met.

420
00:28:09,720 --> 00:28:11,880
But it seems to me,
without your approval...

421
00:28:11,960 --> 00:28:13,800
we will make no sense at all.

422
00:28:14,840 --> 00:28:17,160
That is why I'm asking for...

423
00:28:17,240 --> 00:28:20,800
the clearest possible statement
of what your attitude is going to be.

424
00:28:23,240 --> 00:28:25,760
I appreciate that, Doctor.

425
00:28:25,800 --> 00:28:29,160
It's almost in the form
of an ultimatum.

426
00:28:29,880 --> 00:28:32,640
Not quite, Mr. Drayton.

427
00:28:32,720 --> 00:28:35,480
All you have to say
is good-bye.

428
00:28:39,800 --> 00:28:41,920
Well, that's where it's at.

429
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:45,760
Thank you for the opportunity
to speak my peace.

430
00:28:52,880 --> 00:28:54,600
Well...

431
00:28:54,680 --> 00:28:56,960
still think you ought to have someone
check on him?

432
00:28:57,040 --> 00:28:58,880
No.

433
00:28:58,960 --> 00:29:00,800
He's right about Joey too.

434
00:29:00,880 --> 00:29:02,960
- You know that, don't you?
- Yes.

435
00:29:03,040 --> 00:29:06,880
Thank God he is. That's the way I feel.
Thank God he's right.

436
00:29:06,960 --> 00:29:08,800
She's 23 years old,
and the way she is...

437
00:29:08,840 --> 00:29:12,320
is just exactly the way
we brought her up to be.

438
00:29:12,400 --> 00:29:14,960
We answered her questions.
She listened to our answers.

439
00:29:15,040 --> 00:29:17,160
We told her it was wrong
to believe...

440
00:29:17,200 --> 00:29:21,080
that white people were somehow
essentially superior to black people...

441
00:29:21,160 --> 00:29:24,000
or the brown or the red
or the yellow ones, for that matter.

442
00:29:24,080 --> 00:29:26,920
People who thought that way
were wrong to think that way.

443
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:31,800
Sometimes hateful, usually stupid,
but always wrong.

444
00:29:31,880 --> 00:29:34,280
That's what we said...

445
00:29:34,320 --> 00:29:38,480
and when we said it,
we did not add...

446
00:29:38,560 --> 00:29:40,960
"But don't ever fall in love
with a colored man."

447
00:29:46,120 --> 00:29:48,000
Edie, Mr. Drayton.
Do you want the whole story?

448
00:29:48,040 --> 00:29:51,040
- Yeah, what is it, Edie?
- He's an important guy.

449
00:29:51,120 --> 00:29:53,920
Just the main points:
Born Los Angeles, 1930...

450
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:56,960
graduated maxima cum laude
John Hopkins, '54...

451
00:29:57,040 --> 00:29:59,760
assistant professor,
Yale Medical School, '55...

452
00:29:59,800 --> 00:30:02,600
three years professor,
London School of Tropical Medicine...

453
00:30:02,680 --> 00:30:05,560
three years assistant director,
World Health Organization...

454
00:30:05,640 --> 00:30:09,200
two textbooks and a list of monographs
and medical society honors...

455
00:30:09,280 --> 00:30:10,760
as long as your arm.

456
00:30:10,840 --> 00:30:15,040
Married Elizabeth Bowers, 1955,
one son, John Wade.

457
00:30:15,120 --> 00:30:18,800
Oh, both killed in an accident
in 1959.

458
00:30:18,880 --> 00:30:21,600
- There's a lot more here.
- No, that's all right. Thanks.

459
00:30:36,680 --> 00:30:38,960
What's the $2.20?

460
00:30:39,040 --> 00:30:41,760
He made a call to Los Angeles
to his parents.

461
00:30:41,840 --> 00:30:45,800
I guess he doesn't bum
free telephone calls either.

462
00:30:45,880 --> 00:30:49,160
I can certainly understand why he didn't
have much to say about himself.

463
00:30:49,240 --> 00:30:51,680
Who the hell would believe him?

464
00:30:57,720 --> 00:30:59,600
I beg your pardon, lady.

465
00:30:59,640 --> 00:31:01,520
He loves me, he loves me not.

466
00:31:03,240 --> 00:31:06,960
Tell me, what do you think? Aren't they
exactly the way I said they were?

467
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:09,120
I must admit,
they are very special people.

468
00:31:09,200 --> 00:31:11,200
- Shall I tell you something?
- What's that?

469
00:31:11,280 --> 00:31:13,920
For a whole week,
I've been nervous.

470
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:16,320
No. I don't believe it.

471
00:31:16,400 --> 00:31:19,440
Not about what they'd ultimately feel.
Just about their first reaction.

472
00:31:19,520 --> 00:31:22,440
I thought it was just possible
for the first time in 23 years...

473
00:31:22,520 --> 00:31:24,640
they might let me down
for the first half hour.

474
00:31:24,720 --> 00:31:28,200
You're a phony. You know that?
You're a big phony.

475
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:52,560
Well...

476
00:31:54,200 --> 00:31:57,680
She's always been
a happy human being.

477
00:31:57,760 --> 00:32:01,000
She laughed out loud
before she was six months old.

478
00:32:02,120 --> 00:32:04,280
She was happy as a baby.

479
00:32:04,360 --> 00:32:08,120
Happy as a little girl.
Happy all through school and college.

480
00:32:10,560 --> 00:32:13,960
But I don't think
I've ever seen her...

481
00:32:14,040 --> 00:32:17,160
quite so happy
as she is right now.

482
00:32:18,520 --> 00:32:23,240
And I have to be happy
for her, Matt.

483
00:32:23,320 --> 00:32:24,840
And I am.

484
00:32:25,880 --> 00:32:29,840
I feel happy for her.

485
00:32:31,840 --> 00:32:35,520
And proud of the fact
that we helped make her.

486
00:32:35,600 --> 00:32:38,880
And whatever happens now,
I feel glad...

487
00:32:38,960 --> 00:32:41,120
that Joey's Joey.

488
00:33:06,720 --> 00:33:09,560
How are you today?
Having a steak fry, huh?

489
00:33:09,640 --> 00:33:13,280
Well, now, there she is.
How are you today?

490
00:33:13,320 --> 00:33:15,600
Wanna give me a lift to Market Street?
Save me a cab.

491
00:33:15,680 --> 00:33:17,520
You know it, doll.

492
00:33:17,600 --> 00:33:20,240
I hope these is better
than the last we had, hotshot.

493
00:33:20,320 --> 00:33:23,600
Lady, don't look at me. I deliver it.
I don't rustle the cattle.

494
00:33:23,640 --> 00:33:26,280
You said to remind you
to open the wine.

495
00:33:56,200 --> 00:33:58,280
Civil rights is one thing.

496
00:33:58,320 --> 00:34:00,280
This here is something else.

497
00:34:00,360 --> 00:34:02,360
I went out on to the terrace.

498
00:34:02,440 --> 00:34:05,240
Oh, I'll never forget it.
It was so beautiful.

499
00:34:05,280 --> 00:34:08,040
It was already dark
and the moon was rising.

500
00:34:08,120 --> 00:34:10,960
I guess I didn't see him at first
because I was looking at the view.

501
00:34:11,040 --> 00:34:12,520
But he was standing there.

502
00:34:12,600 --> 00:34:15,720
Then all of a sudden
he moved or something, and I jumped.

503
00:34:17,400 --> 00:34:21,400
And he just stood there,
looking at me and sort of...

504
00:34:21,480 --> 00:34:25,680
- Ah, you're burning your shirt.
- Oh, yes. Sort of smiling.

505
00:34:25,720 --> 00:34:28,360
"Hello," I said.
"Who are you?"

506
00:34:29,520 --> 00:34:31,360
And I think he thought I was...

507
00:34:31,440 --> 00:34:33,280
you know, attractive.

508
00:34:34,600 --> 00:34:36,680
Anyway, finally, he said...

509
00:34:36,760 --> 00:34:40,000
"Well, do you think
it could possibly matter?"

510
00:34:40,080 --> 00:34:44,200
- And it's just crazy, and I admit it.
- You'd better let me do this.

511
00:34:44,280 --> 00:34:48,560
But 20 minutes later,
I felt I was in love with him.

512
00:34:48,640 --> 00:34:52,400
Mom, how long did it take you
to fall in love with Dad?

513
00:34:52,480 --> 00:34:56,480
Oh, well, nothing like
so long as 20 minutes.

514
00:34:56,560 --> 00:34:59,160
- You mean, is that really true?
- Yes, that's really true.

515
00:34:59,240 --> 00:35:00,960
Oh, Mom.

516
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:03,280
Joey, I want to ask you something.

517
00:35:03,360 --> 00:35:07,360
How deeply are you and John in...
No, I have no right to ask.

518
00:35:07,440 --> 00:35:10,640
How deeply involved? Do you mean,
have we been to bed together?

519
00:35:10,720 --> 00:35:12,800
I don't mind you asking me that.
We haven't.

520
00:35:14,960 --> 00:35:16,960
He wouldn't.

521
00:35:17,040 --> 00:35:20,960
I don't think he was in doubt
about my feelings, but he wouldn't.

522
00:35:21,040 --> 00:35:22,880
You're burning my shirt.

523
00:35:22,960 --> 00:35:26,760
He's been concerned the whole time
about my getting hurt somehow.

524
00:35:29,040 --> 00:35:30,960
They're still talking.

525
00:35:31,040 --> 00:35:33,760
Wouldn't you think
they'd have said everything by now?

526
00:35:33,840 --> 00:35:37,520
Are you saying they don't have
any special sense of rhythm?

527
00:35:37,560 --> 00:35:39,200
That's right.

528
00:35:39,280 --> 00:35:41,280
But, hell, you can see it.

529
00:35:41,360 --> 00:35:44,720
You can't turn on the television set
without seeing those kids dancing...

530
00:35:44,800 --> 00:35:47,200
and I say the colored kids
are better than the white kids.

531
00:35:47,280 --> 00:35:51,360
But there's an explanation for that.
It's our dancing, and it's our music.

532
00:35:51,440 --> 00:35:53,120
We brought it here.

533
00:35:53,200 --> 00:35:55,400
I mean, you can do the Watusi...

534
00:35:55,440 --> 00:35:58,960
but we are the Watusi,
if you know what I mean.

535
00:35:59,040 --> 00:36:00,880
I remember,
when I was about your age...

536
00:36:00,920 --> 00:36:05,880
my sports editor telling me that Negroes
would never be able to play baseball.

537
00:36:05,960 --> 00:36:07,800
Now, I suppose if he wanted to...

538
00:36:07,880 --> 00:36:10,360
Willie Mays could be elected
mayor of San Francisco.

539
00:36:10,440 --> 00:36:13,200
I own a newspaper,
but I couldn't be elected dogcatcher.

540
00:36:13,280 --> 00:36:17,080
Well, I don't guess
you want to be dogcatcher any more...

541
00:36:17,160 --> 00:36:19,120
than he wants to be
mayor of San Francisco.

542
00:36:19,200 --> 00:36:21,040
No, I suppose that's right.

543
00:36:23,760 --> 00:36:27,400
Doctor, we've talked about
a good many things...

544
00:36:27,480 --> 00:36:30,160
but there's one thing
we haven't talked about.

545
00:36:30,240 --> 00:36:33,600
Have you given any thought to
the problems your children will have?

546
00:36:33,680 --> 00:36:38,440
Yes, and they'll have some.
And we'll have the children.

547
00:36:38,520 --> 00:36:41,560
Otherwise,
you couldn't call it a marriage.

548
00:36:42,320 --> 00:36:43,840
Is that the way Joey feels?

549
00:36:45,040 --> 00:36:48,160
She feels that all of our children will
be president of the United States...

550
00:36:48,240 --> 00:36:50,080
and they'll all have
colorful administrations.

551
00:36:54,560 --> 00:36:56,400
Well, you made her, Mr. Drayton.

552
00:36:56,480 --> 00:36:59,080
I just met her in Hawaii.

553
00:36:59,120 --> 00:37:01,520
But how do you feel
about that problem?

554
00:37:01,600 --> 00:37:06,160
Well, frankly, I think your daughter
is a bit optimistic.

555
00:37:06,240 --> 00:37:08,360
I'd settle
for secretary of state.

556
00:37:13,800 --> 00:37:17,080
Would you think it was some kind
of cowardice if I told you...

557
00:37:17,160 --> 00:37:20,920
that no matter how confident you two are
I'm just a little scared.

558
00:37:20,960 --> 00:37:23,000
No, it wouldn't.

559
00:37:24,080 --> 00:37:26,480
But you never know.
Things are changing.

560
00:37:27,480 --> 00:37:29,840
I have a feeling they're
not changing anywhere else...

561
00:37:29,920 --> 00:37:31,880
as fast as they are
in my own backyard.

562
00:37:31,960 --> 00:37:34,240
Just tell me this.

563
00:37:34,320 --> 00:37:36,160
Don't you think this quick decision...

564
00:37:36,240 --> 00:37:39,920
about how we feel about this thing
is just a little unfair?

565
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:41,560
In a way, I do.

566
00:37:45,520 --> 00:37:49,520
But it wasn't my idea
that everything be settled so quickly.

567
00:37:49,560 --> 00:37:52,200
Your daughter said
there's no problem.

568
00:37:52,280 --> 00:37:56,760
She says, "My dad is a lifelong fighting
liberal who loathes race prejudice...

569
00:37:56,840 --> 00:37:59,560
and has spent his whole life
fighting against discrimination."

570
00:37:59,640 --> 00:38:03,360
She said, "My parents...
They'll welcome you with open arms."

571
00:38:03,400 --> 00:38:05,320
And I said...

572
00:38:05,360 --> 00:38:07,640
"Oh, I sure want to meet them."

573
00:38:10,560 --> 00:38:12,320
Telephone!
It's Los Angeles!

574
00:38:13,600 --> 00:38:15,440
- Take it in my study.
- Thank you.

575
00:38:30,040 --> 00:38:31,960
- Hello?
- Dr. Prentice?

576
00:38:32,040 --> 00:38:34,680
- Yes, this is he.
- Hello. That you, Little John?

577
00:38:34,760 --> 00:38:37,560
Hi, Dad. What's up, man?
Dr. Graves call again?

578
00:38:37,640 --> 00:38:41,200
Oh, no, it's not that, son.
I just had an idea.

579
00:38:41,280 --> 00:38:44,800
What would you say to us
flying up there to spend the evening?

580
00:38:44,840 --> 00:38:47,760
- This evening?
- We could be up there at 6:30.

581
00:38:47,840 --> 00:38:51,520
I thought maybe we could take you
and your young lady friend for dinner.

582
00:38:51,600 --> 00:38:53,640
- Tell them to come to dinner.
- Just a minute.

583
00:38:53,720 --> 00:38:56,440
- I'm having dinner with her folks.
- Don't be silly.

584
00:38:56,480 --> 00:38:59,080
- Tell them they're invited to dinner.
- Who's that speaking? The young lady?

585
00:38:59,160 --> 00:39:00,680
Yes, that's her.

586
00:39:00,760 --> 00:39:03,560
No, just a minute. You haven't asked
your mother, and there's Tillie.

587
00:39:03,560 --> 00:39:07,000
Won't you come to dinner,
you and Mrs. Prentice?

588
00:39:07,080 --> 00:39:08,560
John and I will meet your plane.

589
00:39:08,640 --> 00:39:10,800
- Stop butting in.
- Who am I talking to? John?

590
00:39:10,880 --> 00:39:12,240
Hi, Dad.

591
00:39:12,280 --> 00:39:16,280
Looks like she wants us
even if you don't. We want to meet her.

592
00:39:16,320 --> 00:39:19,600
- So we'll see you at 6:30. What?
- Oh, no.

593
00:39:19,680 --> 00:39:22,480
- See?
- Your mother says she's pleased.

594
00:39:22,520 --> 00:39:25,400
Oh, hell, he knows that.
All right, son.

595
00:39:25,440 --> 00:39:27,760
- Dad!
- We'll see you later. Bye.

596
00:39:30,800 --> 00:39:32,160
What's the matter?

597
00:39:33,200 --> 00:39:34,720
Mom!

598
00:39:36,080 --> 00:39:39,000
John's father and mother
are coming to dinner.

599
00:39:39,080 --> 00:39:40,920
Oh, good.

600
00:39:41,000 --> 00:39:43,200
- Marvelous.
- We'll meet their plane at 6:30.

601
00:39:43,280 --> 00:39:45,160
Fine.
You'll tell Tillie, won't you?

602
00:39:47,160 --> 00:39:50,800
I told you,
my folks, they don't...

603
00:39:50,880 --> 00:39:52,960
They think
you're a colored girl.

604
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:55,680
- Why didn't you tell them?
- I was gonna write to them.

605
00:39:55,760 --> 00:39:57,440
What difference does it make?

606
00:39:57,520 --> 00:40:00,480
Do you think they wouldn't come?
Call them back and tell them.

607
00:40:00,520 --> 00:40:03,480
They're gonna know anyway at 6:30
because I'll go with you to meet them.

608
00:40:03,520 --> 00:40:05,920
That's not a good idea.
I'll meet them.

609
00:40:05,960 --> 00:40:08,880
It gives me a chance to explain.
I have to explain.

610
00:40:08,960 --> 00:40:11,520
Why do you keep trying
to dramatize everything?

611
00:40:11,600 --> 00:40:15,160
Look, I've told Pete and Judith that
we'll meet them for a drink at 5:30.

612
00:40:15,200 --> 00:40:17,560
It gives us just enough time
to get to the airport.

613
00:40:17,640 --> 00:40:20,920
She's my best and oldest friend
so you've just got to let them meet you.

614
00:40:24,920 --> 00:40:27,240
Did he tell you
about this medical plan of his?

615
00:40:27,320 --> 00:40:28,840
No. What?

616
00:40:28,920 --> 00:40:31,640
It's the damndest thing
you ever heard of.

617
00:40:31,720 --> 00:40:34,600
They put a whole medical school
on about 20 trucks.

618
00:40:34,680 --> 00:40:37,400
Then they run
into some African country...

619
00:40:37,480 --> 00:40:40,680
pick up the brightest native kids...
hundreds at a time...

620
00:40:40,760 --> 00:40:44,400
and put them through courses just like
they do the U.S. Army Corpsmen.

621
00:40:44,480 --> 00:40:47,200
Only his idea is
that they're all specialists.

622
00:40:47,280 --> 00:40:49,640
You know, each one trained
to do one simple thing...

623
00:40:49,720 --> 00:40:55,000
like sewing up a wound
or delivering a baby or what have you.

624
00:40:55,080 --> 00:40:58,680
They go into places where people
have never heard of an aspirin tablet...

625
00:40:58,760 --> 00:41:01,200
let alone a doctor.

626
00:41:01,280 --> 00:41:03,640
Imagine what that means.

627
00:41:03,720 --> 00:41:07,440
For every thousand kids they train,
they can save a million lives a year.

628
00:41:07,480 --> 00:41:09,360
Now just think of that.

629
00:41:09,400 --> 00:41:11,880
He seems to have made
quite an impression on you.

630
00:41:11,960 --> 00:41:13,920
Yeah.

631
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:18,440
I asked him how he got so far.
You know, he's only 37.

632
00:41:18,440 --> 00:41:23,120
He said he thought he got the best
breaks because everybody he met...

633
00:41:23,160 --> 00:41:26,480
didn't want him to think
they were prejudiced against him.

634
00:41:26,560 --> 00:41:29,600
Yeah, he made an impression, all right.
I wouldn't know how to fault him.

635
00:41:29,680 --> 00:41:31,720
Are you trying to fault him?

636
00:41:31,800 --> 00:41:35,160
No, I'm not trying to fault him.
You know, his father is a mailman.

637
00:41:35,240 --> 00:41:37,600
Retired now.
Lives in Los Angeles.

638
00:41:37,680 --> 00:41:40,920
Now how do you suppose
a colored mailman...

639
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:44,640
produced a son
with all the qualities he has?

640
00:41:44,680 --> 00:41:47,600
- You'll find out this evening.
- What?

641
00:41:49,400 --> 00:41:51,040
Guess who's coming to dinner?

642
00:41:51,080 --> 00:41:52,760
Who?

643
00:41:52,840 --> 00:41:54,840
You mean, his parents?

644
00:41:56,360 --> 00:41:57,760
Now wait a minute.

645
00:41:59,240 --> 00:42:01,400
- Whose idea was that?
- Joey invited them.

646
00:42:01,480 --> 00:42:05,720
Yeah, Joey. We're being pressurized.
You know that, don't you?

647
00:42:06,720 --> 00:42:09,960
First there wasn't gonna be a marriage
unless we approved.

648
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:12,560
Then we had one day
to make up our minds.

649
00:42:12,640 --> 00:42:15,520
Now we have to spend hours entertaining
somebody we never heard of.

650
00:42:15,560 --> 00:42:17,880
What the hell
is coming off here?

651
00:42:21,960 --> 00:42:25,120
Oh, don't look at
those baby pictures.

652
00:42:25,200 --> 00:42:27,520
That was at Klosters,
the year before last.

653
00:42:27,560 --> 00:42:29,440
I'll get it!
Just a second.

654
00:42:34,120 --> 00:42:36,560
Monsignor Ryan!
How wonderful to see you.

655
00:42:36,640 --> 00:42:38,960
- Well, good afternoon.
- Come on in. Good afternoon.

656
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:41,400
Why are you here
when you should be in Hawaii?

657
00:42:41,440 --> 00:42:45,520
What is the problem that caused your
father to chicken out on our golf game?

658
00:42:45,560 --> 00:42:50,040
- Who is this gentleman?
- Monsignor, this is Dr. John Prentice.

659
00:42:50,120 --> 00:42:53,000
We met in Hawaii 11 days ago.
The two of us are going to be married.

660
00:42:53,000 --> 00:42:57,200
Are you, indeed?
I take it you mean to each other.

661
00:42:57,280 --> 00:42:59,160
- Dr. Prentice.
- Monsignor.

662
00:42:59,240 --> 00:43:01,520
Well, of course,
you're the problem.

663
00:43:01,600 --> 00:43:04,040
I'm afraid I am.

664
00:43:04,120 --> 00:43:06,960
I knew nothing of this.
Why haven't your parents informed me?

665
00:43:07,040 --> 00:43:09,280
They didn't know either.
We only flew back this morning.

666
00:43:09,360 --> 00:43:12,160
Excuse me a second.
I forgot to tell Tillie something.

667
00:43:14,240 --> 00:43:15,720
Well...

668
00:43:16,960 --> 00:43:19,920
- This was all very sudden, was it not?
- Yes, it was.

669
00:43:20,000 --> 00:43:22,360
I suppose you two have had time
to consider what you're doing.

670
00:43:22,440 --> 00:43:24,600
No, we've not.

671
00:43:26,200 --> 00:43:28,520
We'll be two more for dinner.
How many steaks did you get?

672
00:43:28,560 --> 00:43:30,840
I got four
'cause I was told four.

673
00:43:30,880 --> 00:43:33,240
Order two more because the doctor's
father and mother are coming.

674
00:43:33,280 --> 00:43:37,080
- We'll be six.
- His father and mother! Here?

675
00:43:37,160 --> 00:43:39,440
That's right.
If the butcher can't send 'em...

676
00:43:39,520 --> 00:43:42,040
tell him to put 'em
in a taxi.

677
00:43:42,120 --> 00:43:45,440
It's gettin' more like
a holy rollers meetin' every minute.

678
00:43:45,480 --> 00:43:48,560
Of course!
I know about you.

679
00:43:48,600 --> 00:43:51,040
I read an article about you
in "Common Wheel."

680
00:43:51,080 --> 00:43:53,760
I shall want to talk to you
about that.

681
00:43:53,840 --> 00:43:56,720
You know, this fellow you brought home
is a very important man?

682
00:43:56,760 --> 00:43:59,120
- Are you aware of that?
- I'm wholly aware of it.

683
00:43:59,200 --> 00:44:01,840
When I'm married to him,
I'll be important.

684
00:44:01,920 --> 00:44:05,120
I guess you will,
as a matter of fact.

685
00:44:05,160 --> 00:44:07,600
- Where's Arnold Palmer?
- Dad and Mom are in the garden.

686
00:44:07,680 --> 00:44:10,960
Good. Well, just go on
with what you're doing. Fore!

687
00:44:12,640 --> 00:44:15,280
Of all the friends we've ever had,
I guess he's the closest.

688
00:44:15,360 --> 00:44:18,760
We're not Catholics, but he and Dad
and Mom have done things together.

689
00:44:18,840 --> 00:44:21,760
You know,
sat on committees and things.

690
00:44:21,800 --> 00:44:24,640
He's a wonderful man,
and we love him.

691
00:44:26,800 --> 00:44:29,200
You're a remarkable fellow, Mike.

692
00:44:29,280 --> 00:44:31,200
You get younger every minute.

693
00:44:31,280 --> 00:44:34,320
- Did you...
- Yes, I've just seen him.

694
00:44:34,400 --> 00:44:36,400
Handsome fellow, isn't he?

695
00:44:36,480 --> 00:44:38,360
Little Joey is nothing less
than radiant.

696
00:44:38,400 --> 00:44:41,520
It warms me chilly old heart
just to look at her.

697
00:44:41,600 --> 00:44:43,640
Aren't you just
a little shocked?

698
00:44:43,720 --> 00:44:46,960
Shocked?
Why should I be shocked?

699
00:44:47,040 --> 00:44:51,000
I've known a good many cases
of marriages between races in my time.

700
00:44:51,040 --> 00:44:54,160
Strangely enough,
they usually work out quite well.

701
00:44:54,240 --> 00:44:55,880
I don't know why.

702
00:44:55,960 --> 00:44:59,080
Maybe because it requires
some special quality of effort...

703
00:44:59,160 --> 00:45:01,360
more consideration and compassion...

704
00:45:01,440 --> 00:45:05,160
than most marriages
seem to generate these days.

705
00:45:05,200 --> 00:45:09,040
- Could that be it?
- Yes, it could.

706
00:45:09,120 --> 00:45:12,320
I'm glad you said that.
That's a beautiful thought.

707
00:45:12,400 --> 00:45:15,240
You do have beautiful thoughts.

708
00:45:15,320 --> 00:45:17,160
That's my trade, you know.

709
00:45:18,920 --> 00:45:23,040
What about laddie over here?
You making heavy weather of it?

710
00:45:24,240 --> 00:45:27,520
You know, this man is quite
a famous fellow in his own right.

711
00:45:27,560 --> 00:45:32,000
He's done incredible work in Asia
and some awful place in Africa.

712
00:45:32,080 --> 00:45:35,200
Mom! Hilary's here.
She wants to see you.

713
00:45:36,880 --> 00:45:41,320
Excuse me, will you? Express some more
beautiful thoughts to the lad there.

714
00:45:45,840 --> 00:45:47,680
Thank you.

715
00:45:47,760 --> 00:45:50,640
I hope you won't think
that I'm prying, Doctor...

716
00:45:50,720 --> 00:45:53,600
but naturally
one is curious.

717
00:45:53,680 --> 00:45:56,800
- Naturally.
- We are going to be married.

718
00:45:58,160 --> 00:46:00,080
Are you?

719
00:46:00,160 --> 00:46:02,160
Well, I didn't even know.

720
00:46:02,200 --> 00:46:04,360
I mean, Christina
hadn't even mentioned that...

721
00:46:04,440 --> 00:46:06,680
She didn't know.
It was a surprise to her too.

722
00:46:06,760 --> 00:46:10,680
A surprise.
Well, I should think it was.

723
00:46:10,760 --> 00:46:11,800
My dear!

724
00:46:11,880 --> 00:46:15,880
Joey tells me that congratulations
are in order, and you didn't even know.

725
00:46:23,440 --> 00:46:27,600
What's the problem, Hilary?
What brings you all the way up here?

726
00:46:28,880 --> 00:46:32,960
- Mr. Cazalet phoned about the pictures.
- Oh, that. Excuse us, will you?

727
00:46:33,040 --> 00:46:35,080
I'll walk out to your car
with you.

728
00:46:35,120 --> 00:46:37,600
- I hope I'll be seeing you shortly.
- Actually, no.

729
00:46:37,640 --> 00:46:39,880
Dr. Prentice is leaving tonight...

730
00:46:39,960 --> 00:46:42,840
and Joey within
the next couple of weeks.

731
00:46:42,920 --> 00:46:46,280
Well, then you must permit me
to wish you every happiness.

732
00:46:46,360 --> 00:46:48,480
Come along.

733
00:46:53,720 --> 00:46:56,080
My poor dear,
what a shock for you.

734
00:46:56,160 --> 00:46:58,640
I knew something was up
when I came into the gallery.

735
00:46:58,720 --> 00:47:01,040
But this!
Whatever are you going to do about it?

736
00:47:01,120 --> 00:47:03,960
- I mean, the child is of age.
- Yes, the child is 23.

737
00:47:04,000 --> 00:47:08,200
Why didn't you simply ring up
with the Cazalet information?

738
00:47:08,280 --> 00:47:10,960
Well, I must admit,
I was intensely curious.

739
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:12,520
I couldn't believe it.

740
00:47:12,600 --> 00:47:16,000
It's so unlike Joey to do anything
so appallingly stupid.

741
00:47:16,080 --> 00:47:19,040
- Yes, come along.
- But what you must be going through.

742
00:47:19,120 --> 00:47:21,400
You must try not to worry about it.

743
00:47:22,400 --> 00:47:24,600
Now I have some instructions
for you.

744
00:47:24,680 --> 00:47:27,520
I want you to go straight back
to the gallery. Start your motor.

745
00:47:27,600 --> 00:47:29,440
When you to the gallery,
tell Jennifer...

746
00:47:29,520 --> 00:47:31,400
she will be looking after things
temporarily.

747
00:47:31,480 --> 00:47:34,440
She's to give me a ring if there's
anything she can't deal with herself.

748
00:47:34,520 --> 00:47:38,400
Then go into the office
and make out a check for cash...

749
00:47:38,480 --> 00:47:40,960
for the sum of $5,000.

750
00:47:41,040 --> 00:47:43,400
Then carefully...

751
00:47:43,480 --> 00:47:45,680
remove absolutely everything...

752
00:47:45,760 --> 00:47:48,920
that might subsequently remind me
that you had ever been there...

753
00:47:48,960 --> 00:47:51,320
including that yellow thing
with the blue bulbs...

754
00:47:51,360 --> 00:47:53,240
which you have
such an affection for.

755
00:47:53,280 --> 00:47:55,920
Then take the check for $5,000...

756
00:47:55,960 --> 00:47:57,840
which I feel you deserve...

757
00:47:57,920 --> 00:48:01,680
and get permanently lost.

758
00:48:01,760 --> 00:48:04,360
It's not that I don't want
to know you, although I don't.

759
00:48:04,440 --> 00:48:07,760
It's just that I'm afraid
we're not really the sort of people...

760
00:48:07,840 --> 00:48:10,520
that you can afford
to be associated with.

761
00:48:10,600 --> 00:48:13,400
Don't speak.
Just go.

762
00:48:19,120 --> 00:48:21,440
You see that boy?
The tall one?

763
00:48:21,480 --> 00:48:24,240
If he'd played his cards right,
you'd never even have met me.

764
00:48:24,320 --> 00:48:26,920
But he fell for some girl
from Pomona.

765
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:28,200
- That'll teach him.
- Mom!

766
00:48:28,280 --> 00:48:31,880
Do you know what Hilary was doing?
She was being an absolute bitch.

767
00:48:31,960 --> 00:48:35,600
She was. I almost wish you'd fire her.
I really do.

768
00:48:35,680 --> 00:48:39,040
Joey, how can you be so hard?

769
00:48:39,120 --> 00:48:42,640
She has a really quite ruthless streak.
You ought to be warned about it.

770
00:48:42,680 --> 00:48:44,640
She gets it
from her father.

771
00:48:45,760 --> 00:48:48,640
They need all the help
you can give them...

772
00:48:48,720 --> 00:48:52,240
because they're going to have
special difficulties.

773
00:48:52,320 --> 00:48:54,760
No, don't budge.
Please, sit.

774
00:48:54,840 --> 00:48:56,840
Of course, they know all that.

775
00:48:56,920 --> 00:48:59,960
They're serious people.
Fine, intelligent people.

776
00:49:00,040 --> 00:49:02,040
And if they know
what lies in store for them...

777
00:49:02,120 --> 00:49:05,400
and they still want each other
enough to accept it...

778
00:49:05,440 --> 00:49:08,280
I think it's plain as anything
that they love each other very much.

779
00:49:08,360 --> 00:49:11,200
You'll have to agree that any two people
who love each other that much...

780
00:49:11,280 --> 00:49:14,040
deserve all the best luck
in the world.

781
00:49:15,120 --> 00:49:16,680
I don't know.

782
00:49:16,760 --> 00:49:19,200
I wish I didn't have the feeling
that they'll never make it...

783
00:49:19,280 --> 00:49:21,120
that the whole thing's
impossible.

784
00:49:23,240 --> 00:49:25,120
You feel that way, do you?

785
00:49:26,600 --> 00:49:28,440
You're really thrashing about then.

786
00:49:29,760 --> 00:49:32,040
That's very interesting, indeed.

787
00:49:32,120 --> 00:49:34,840
And rather amusing, too,
to see a broken-down...

788
00:49:34,920 --> 00:49:38,640
old phony liberal come face-to-face
with his principles.

789
00:49:39,760 --> 00:49:41,200
Of course,
I always have believed...

790
00:49:41,280 --> 00:49:44,040
that in that
fighting liberal facade...

791
00:49:44,080 --> 00:49:47,800
there must be some sort
of reactionary bigot trying to get out.

792
00:49:47,880 --> 00:49:51,840
Oh, go to hell. You and your crowd
are still preaching hell.

793
00:49:53,120 --> 00:49:55,480
Well, I'm off.

794
00:49:55,560 --> 00:49:58,280
As much as I'm enjoying
your discomfiture...

795
00:49:58,320 --> 00:50:01,160
I may be able to save a few souls
before supper.

796
00:50:01,200 --> 00:50:05,920
But, I am, as it happens,
free for dinner.

797
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:08,240
Please, come, 7:30.

798
00:50:08,320 --> 00:50:11,280
The doctor's family are flying up
from Los Angeles.

799
00:50:11,320 --> 00:50:15,640
Oh, well, in that case,
you'll actually need me.

800
00:50:15,720 --> 00:50:18,640
Otherwise, your side
won't even outnumber the blacks.

801
00:50:19,680 --> 00:50:21,520
Thank you, my dear.

802
00:50:22,960 --> 00:50:24,800
Half past seven.

803
00:50:25,680 --> 00:50:27,960
What was that the Beatles sang?

804
00:50:28,040 --> 00:50:31,000
We can work it out
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah

805
00:50:38,520 --> 00:50:40,520
Mom did it.
Do you think it looks like him?

806
00:50:40,600 --> 00:50:43,280
Well, it looks a little grim,
doesn't it?

807
00:50:43,360 --> 00:50:46,640
- No, don't let me disturb you.
- Not at all.

808
00:50:46,720 --> 00:50:50,360
I hope you don't mind, but I've wrangled
an invitation to dinner.

809
00:50:50,440 --> 00:50:53,040
- Marvelous! I'm delighted you're coming.
- Thank you, my dear.

810
00:50:53,120 --> 00:50:56,000
- I'm very delighted to have met you.
- My pleasure, Monsignor.

811
00:50:56,080 --> 00:50:58,520
- See you this evening.
- Certainly.

812
00:50:58,600 --> 00:51:00,800
You know,
you two make me feel...

813
00:51:00,840 --> 00:51:04,000
quite extraordinarily happy.

814
00:51:08,960 --> 00:51:12,720
I'd better tell Tillie. If you listen,
you'll hear her going through the roof.

815
00:51:18,240 --> 00:51:20,640
I brought you
the latest bulletin.

816
00:51:20,720 --> 00:51:22,960
Guess who's coming
to dinner now?

817
00:51:23,040 --> 00:51:25,840
The Reverend Martin Luther King?

818
00:51:27,440 --> 00:51:29,480
You're so close.
It's Monsignor Ryan.

819
00:51:29,560 --> 00:51:32,640
Bake a second pie, will you?
You know how he loves your cooking.

820
00:51:32,720 --> 00:51:34,680
Listen, is the big guest room
in order?

821
00:51:34,720 --> 00:51:37,280
Dr. Prentice wants to have
a shower and change.

822
00:51:38,360 --> 00:51:41,280
- He does?
- He does.

823
00:51:44,600 --> 00:51:46,520
Well, she's 23 years old.

824
00:51:46,600 --> 00:51:48,520
I guess she has
a right to do as she pleases.

825
00:51:48,560 --> 00:51:50,960
Yes, but that's not the point.
The doctor said...

826
00:51:51,040 --> 00:51:55,600
I know what the doctor said. Could we
get out of here for a few minutes?

827
00:51:55,680 --> 00:51:57,080
- Sure.
- What are the others doing?

828
00:51:57,160 --> 00:51:58,920
They're meeting Peter and Judith
for a drink...

829
00:51:58,960 --> 00:52:00,880
and then they're going on
to the airport.

830
00:52:00,920 --> 00:52:04,040
All right, come on.
Come on, will you?

831
00:52:18,240 --> 00:52:21,080
Whatever happened to what's-his-name?
Homer?

832
00:52:21,120 --> 00:52:23,360
That lawyer?
I thought she liked him very much.

833
00:52:23,400 --> 00:52:26,720
Nothing happened to Homer.
Dr. Prentice just happened to Joey.

834
00:52:26,760 --> 00:52:30,560
It was only last Christmas
she said Homer had the inside track.

835
00:52:32,760 --> 00:52:36,000
Isn't that the place where we got
the good ice cream? Let's get some.

836
00:52:36,080 --> 00:52:38,480
It's after 5:00.
You'll spoil...

837
00:52:38,560 --> 00:52:40,400
A little ice cream can't hurt.

838
00:52:58,600 --> 00:53:01,560
- Yes?
- When I had ice cream before...

839
00:53:01,490 --> 00:53:05,330
I had a special kind of flavor
that I liked very much.

840
00:53:05,370 --> 00:53:08,170
- But I can't remember what it was.
- I'll bring you the list.

841
00:53:08,210 --> 00:53:10,330
No, you must know what it is.

842
00:53:10,410 --> 00:53:13,610
Daiquiri Ice? Honeycomb Candy?
Cocoa Coconut? Jamoca Almond Fudge?

843
00:53:13,690 --> 00:53:16,970
Mocha Jamoca? Peanut Butter and Jelly?
Cinnamon Banana Mint?

844
00:53:17,050 --> 00:53:19,650
- Must have been some other place.
- Fresh Oregon Boysenberry Sherbet?

845
00:53:20,890 --> 00:53:23,010
That's it.

846
00:53:23,050 --> 00:53:26,770
I'm sure that's it. Bring me
a Fresh Oregon Boysenberry.

847
00:53:26,850 --> 00:53:28,690
- Bring me a big one.
- Right.

848
00:53:28,770 --> 00:53:30,730
- Will you have some? It's delicious.
- No. Black coffee.

849
00:53:30,810 --> 00:53:35,730
One double Fresh Oregon Boysenberry
Sherbet and one black coffee. Thanks.

850
00:53:40,890 --> 00:53:43,770
You know, Matt...

851
00:53:43,810 --> 00:53:47,690
I think Mike was right
that Joey is lucky.

852
00:53:47,770 --> 00:53:50,210
The work he's doing
is so important...

853
00:53:50,290 --> 00:53:53,330
she'll be able to help him with it
and share it all with him.

854
00:53:53,410 --> 00:53:55,250
The best break
any wife can have.

855
00:53:56,530 --> 00:53:58,690
You know, for us,
it's all been great...

856
00:53:58,730 --> 00:54:02,490
but do you know
what was the best time of all?

857
00:54:02,570 --> 00:54:04,490
It was in the beginning
when everything was a struggle...

858
00:54:04,570 --> 00:54:09,090
and you were working too hard
and sometimes frightened...

859
00:54:09,130 --> 00:54:11,850
and there were times
when I felt...

860
00:54:11,890 --> 00:54:16,210
that I really knew
that I was a help to you.

861
00:54:16,290 --> 00:54:18,970
That was the very best time of all
for me.

862
00:54:23,090 --> 00:54:25,810
- One black coffee.
- Thank you.

863
00:54:25,890 --> 00:54:28,210
And one Fresh
Oregon Boysenberry Sherbet.

864
00:54:28,250 --> 00:54:30,130
Thank you.

865
00:54:41,250 --> 00:54:43,090
This is not the stuff.

866
00:54:43,170 --> 00:54:45,450
I never had this stuff
before in my life.

867
00:54:53,570 --> 00:54:54,970
You know, it's not bad.

868
00:54:55,010 --> 00:54:57,570
Not bad at all.
I kinda like it.

869
00:54:57,650 --> 00:54:59,530
Fresh Oregon Boysenberry.

870
00:55:00,930 --> 00:55:02,330
Yes, sir.

871
00:55:02,410 --> 00:55:04,570
Well, when I had
the ice cream before...

872
00:55:04,650 --> 00:55:07,130
this isn't the stuff I had,
but I like it.

873
00:55:07,210 --> 00:55:10,010
- It's very good. I like it very much.
- Okay.

874
00:55:20,610 --> 00:55:23,970
- How do you do, Miss Binks?
- I got somethin' to say to you, boy.

875
00:55:24,010 --> 00:55:27,610
Exactly what you tryin' to pull here?

876
00:55:27,690 --> 00:55:31,330
I'm not trying to pull anything.
I was looking to find me a wife.

877
00:55:31,370 --> 00:55:34,850
Ain't that just likely!
You wanna answer me somethin'?

878
00:55:34,930 --> 00:55:37,490
What kinda doctor
you supposed to be anyhow?

879
00:55:37,570 --> 00:55:39,450
Would you believe horse?

880
00:55:40,850 --> 00:55:43,290
You make with witticisms
and all, huh?

881
00:55:43,370 --> 00:55:45,170
Let me tell you somethin'.

882
00:55:45,250 --> 00:55:47,250
You may think you're foolin'
Miss Joey and her folks.

883
00:55:47,330 --> 00:55:50,410
But you ain't foolin' me for a minute.
I see what you are.

884
00:55:50,450 --> 00:55:53,250
You're one of those smooth-talkin',
smart-ass niggers...

885
00:55:53,330 --> 00:55:55,210
just out for all you can get,
with your black power...

886
00:55:55,290 --> 00:55:57,130
and all that other
trouble-makin' nonsense.

887
00:55:57,210 --> 00:56:00,210
And you listen here. I brought up that
child from a baby in her cradle...

888
00:56:00,290 --> 00:56:02,730
and ain't nobody gonna harm her none
while I'm here watchin'.

889
00:56:02,810 --> 00:56:05,930
And as long as you are anywhere around
this house, I'm right here watchin'.

890
00:56:06,010 --> 00:56:08,370
You read me, boy?
You bring any trouble in here...

891
00:56:08,450 --> 00:56:11,450
and you just like to find out
what black power really means!

892
00:56:11,490 --> 00:56:14,730
And furthermore to that,
you ain't all that good-lookin'!

893
00:56:22,730 --> 00:56:24,490
That was very good.

894
00:56:24,570 --> 00:56:28,090
If I come in again, remind me about
the Oregon Boysenberry, will you?

895
00:56:29,210 --> 00:56:31,170
Yeah, I sure will.
Thank you, sir.

896
00:56:34,610 --> 00:56:36,810
Should we take home
a couple of quarts for dessert?

897
00:56:36,890 --> 00:56:38,730
No, Tillie's baked some pies.

898
00:56:49,410 --> 00:56:51,290
You stupid idiot!

899
00:56:54,130 --> 00:56:56,050
Why can't you
look where you're going?

900
00:56:56,130 --> 00:56:58,290
Sorry, son,
but your car is so low...

901
00:56:58,370 --> 00:57:00,330
Of course you didn't see me!

902
00:57:00,410 --> 00:57:02,410
You weren't even looking
where you were going!

903
00:57:02,490 --> 00:57:04,730
Look what you did to my car!

904
00:57:04,810 --> 00:57:06,450
It's my fault.
My insurance...

905
00:57:06,490 --> 00:57:09,130
Yeah, yeah. Who cares
about your lousy insurance?

906
00:57:09,170 --> 00:57:11,090
I worked over three months on that!

907
00:57:11,130 --> 00:57:13,090
How much will it cost
to have it repaired?

908
00:57:13,170 --> 00:57:16,530
Look at it! Thirty or forty bucks
it'll cost. Did you see it?

909
00:57:16,610 --> 00:57:18,690
Stupid old man.
He oughtn't be allowed out.

910
00:57:18,770 --> 00:57:21,090
He ought to be put away someplace
in a home or something.

911
00:57:21,130 --> 00:57:24,770
There's fifty bucks! Don't bother
to have it fixed. Buy a new one!

912
00:57:26,570 --> 00:57:28,610
Some of these old guys,
they're senile!

913
00:57:29,650 --> 00:57:31,370
Stupid old man.

914
00:57:32,170 --> 00:57:34,010
There oughta be a law!

915
00:57:43,770 --> 00:57:46,250
What the hell is it today?

916
00:57:46,330 --> 00:57:49,290
Less than 12'/. Of the people
in this city are colored people.

917
00:57:49,370 --> 00:57:52,210
I can't even have a dish
of Oregon "Boosenberry"...

918
00:57:52,250 --> 00:57:54,130
without runnin' into one of them.

